# OpenSpec — vanilla spec-driven workflow

[OpenSpec](https://github.com/Fission-AI/OpenSpec) structures a change as a validated proposal before
any code: **explore → propose → validate → apply → archive**. Specs are the source of truth; changes
are deltas against them.

## Quick checklist

- Search existing work first: `openspec spec list --long`, `openspec list`.
- Decide scope: new capability vs modify existing capability.
- Pick a unique change-id: kebab-case, **verb-led** (`add-`, `update-`, `remove-`, `refactor-`).
- Scaffold `proposal.md`, `tasks.md`, `design.md` (only if needed), and one delta spec per affected
  capability.
- Validate: `openspec validate <change-id> --strict` — fix until it passes.
- **Do not start implementation until the proposal is approved.**

## When a proposal is required

Create one for: new features/capabilities, breaking changes (API/schema), architecture or pattern
changes, behavior-changing optimizations, security-pattern updates. Skip it for: bug fixes restoring
intended behavior, typos/formatting/comments, non-breaking dependency bumps, config tweaks. Unclear →
propose (safer).

## Lifecycle

| Stage | Command / skill | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| Explore | `/opsx:explore` | Thinking-partner mode: read the codebase, align the requirement — no implementation. |
| Propose | `/opsx:propose <name>` | Creates the change and generates proposal → spec deltas → design → tasks. |
| Validate | `openspec validate <id> --strict` | **Gate before coding.** Fails if a required section is missing. |
| Apply | `/opsx:apply [<id>]` | Reads proposal/specs/design/tasks, implements each task, marks `[x]`. |
| Archive | `/opsx:archive [<id>]` | Verifies completeness, syncs delta specs into `specs/`, moves the change to `archive/`. |

## Artifact formats

**`proposal.md`** — `# Change: <title>`, `## Why` (1–2 sentences), `## What Changes` (bullets; mark
**BREAKING**), `## Impact` (affected specs + code).

**Spec deltas** — `changes/<id>/specs/<capability>/spec.md`, one file per affected capability:

```markdown
## ADDED Requirements
### Requirement: <name>
The system SHALL ...

#### Scenario: <case>
- **WHEN** ...
- **THEN** ...

## MODIFIED Requirements   (repeat the complete modified requirement)
## REMOVED Requirements    (add **Reason** and **Migration**)
```

Every requirement needs at least one `#### Scenario:`. `--strict` enforces this.

**`tasks.md`** — numbered groups of checkboxes (`- [ ] 1.1 ...`). Mark `[x]` immediately after each
task is done and validated, not in a batch at the end.

**`design.md`** — only when the change is cross-cutting, adds a dependency, touches data models,
has security/performance/migration complexity, or has open technical decisions. Skeleton:
`## Context`, `## Goals / Non-Goals`, `## Decisions` (with alternatives considered), `## Risks /
Trade-offs`, `## Migration`.

## Directory layout

```
openspec/
  project.md                # project conventions the AI must follow
  specs/<capability>/spec.md      # current truth (updated only at archive)
  changes/<change-id>/            # active proposal
    proposal.md  design.md  tasks.md  specs/<capability>/spec.md
  changes/archive/<date>-<id>/    # completed changes = history + delta base
```

## Execution rules

- Always run `openspec validate <id> --strict` **before** implementing — it is the gate, not a
  formality.
- Never edit generated `/opsx` skills or `schema.yaml` by hand; they change via the CLI
  (`openspec update`) or a deliberate fork.
- Current specs live in `openspec/specs/`; `archive/` is history and the base for future deltas.

